summary.seg: The manuscript contains a collection of Greek texts on rhetoric, by Hermogenes (ca. 160-before 230 CE), Hephaestion (2nd c. CE), and Dionysius of Halicarnassus (ca. 60 - after 7 BCE). Hermogenes, a rhetorician born in Tarsos, is known as the author of a series of treatises on rhetoric, which enjoyed a great success, becoming canonical texts for the teaching of rhetoric in Byzantium, being read and commented on until the Renaissance. The Alexandrian grammarian Hephaestion wrote a treatise On Metres in 48 books, which was reduced to an Enchiridion, a handbook, in a single book, present in this manuscript with other texts by him.

The manuscript, on the basis of the script and of the watermarks, is datable to the second half of the 15th century. One scribe started the copy and another, with a more informal script, took over, and wrote a commentary in Latin at the end of the manuscript.

support.material:
ff. 2-[134], [III]-[VIII] Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermarks:
ff. 2-30, 41-111, 112/123 Ladder with 4 rungs ( ca. 50 23 ) in the gutter, comparable to Briquet Échelle 5905 , which is dated to 1450-1452 and 1453-1454, and to Harlfinger Échelle 14 , which is dated to 1484.
ff. 33/38 Eagle ( ca. 50 45 ) in the gutter, not entirely visible, comparable to the types Briquet Aigle 82 , which is dated to 1479, and Harlfinger Aigle 21-22 , which are dated to 1495 and ± 1495.
ff. 35-36 Scissors ( ca. 50 45 ) in the gutter, not entirely visible, comparable to the types Briquet Ciseaux 3767 , which is dated to 1479 and 1483, and Harlfinger Ciseaux 83 , which is dated to 1456.
ff. 113-122, 124, 125-134, [III-{VII] Cardinal's hat ( ca. 40 35 ) in the gutter, not entirely visible, the visible details are too few to try an identification; the lower part, which is best visible, is comparable to the type Harlfinger Chapeau 17-18 , which are dated to 1475 and 1479.

ff. [I]-II Western paper, folded in octavo. Watermark: A watermark with a rooster (?) in a circle surmounted by grapes and letters ( I V I ?) is faintly visible on f. [I] recto. It looks like a later watermark. Paper leaves have been pasted on ff. [I]-II, therefore it is not possible to see clearly.

foliation.p: Foliation in ink on the top right hand corner recto, starting from 2; ff. 1, 10 are missing; the numbers 118-119 do not appear in the sequence, but no leaves are missing; the numbers 132 and 134 are not visible any more due to damage. At the beginning there are two endleaves (only on the second the numeral II is visible), at the end there are 6 unnumbered blank leaves (ff. [III]-[VIII]; ff. [a] and [b] are two unnumbered later endleaves, which were added with the binding; [a] + [I]-II + 2-9, 11-117, 120-131, [132], 133, [134] + [III]-[VIII] + [b]

collation.p: Quire 1 is a bifolium formed of endleaves of a paper with different format and age from the rest of the manuscript. Quire 2 was a quinion which lost a bifolium (ff. [1]/[10]), with loss of text. Quire 8 is a quinion in which a single leaf of smaller dimension was inserted (f. 67).

signatures.p: Modern numbering of the quires in pencil, from 4 ( f. 31r) to 13 ( f. 125r), in the lower right corner of the recto of the first leaves of the quires.

The remains of quire numbering in ink are visible throughout: the quires are indicated with Greek or Latin letters, and the first 4 leaves are numbered 1 to 4: the series is not immediately understandable:
γ f. 23r
c (or a round ε?) f. 41r, see also c2 f. 42r
d f. 53r
δ 4 f. 66r
ε f. 74r
ϛ 2 f. 85r
ζ f. 92r.

supportDesc.condition:
The manuscript is in fair condition. There are water and humidity stains throughout, but the text is always readable. The first and last leaves, ff. [I] recto and [VIII] verso, are very stained. In order to reinforce them, paper leaves have been pasted to ff. [I]-II; paper strips have been pasted to the external margin of ff. 2-3 and
[VII]-[VIII]. The bifolium formed by ff. 106-107 has been bound inside out, generating disorder in the succession of the text; this happened before the foliation was written, as it does not reflect the correct order of the text. Paper is soft at the corners of the leaves.

layoutDesc.layout: ff. 2r-6r A single column of 26 lines. ca. 145 85
ff. 7r-124v A single column of 28 lines. ca. 150 90
ff. 125r-[134]v A single column of 35-38 lines, blank margins on the left and lower part of the leaves. ca. 190 ca. 105-115

handNote.p: f. 2r-6v l. 9 Hand A: a humanistic, round minuscule script of small and regular size, neat and tidy, vertical, which can be included in the group of Greek scripts of the 15th century similar to the hand of Manuel Chrysoloras (it is comparbale to the sober group in P. Eleuteri, P. Canart, Scrittura greca nell'Umanesimo italiano, Milano 1991).
The text is written in brown ink.

f. 6r l. 10-36v, 41r-[134]v Hand B: a minuscule script slanting to the right, fluent, with many ligatures, also datable to the 15th century and associated with a more recherché class of scripts. The scribe does not write iota subscript.

From f. 125r the script becomes more rapid, almost nervous, and slants more decidely to the right. Although M. R. James thought it a later hand, the coincidence of forms and ligatures indicate that it is still hand B: for example triangular phi, round sigma of larger size, the ligatures epsilon-omega with epsilon reduced to a loop, tau-alpha from below et c. Hand B writes also the Latin text from f. 125r.
The text is written in brown ink.

decoDesc.decoNote: Sometimes, to mark the passage from one text to another, the scribe traced very simple friezes as line fillers, see ff. 21r, 122v.

additions.p: Another hand wrote notes in the lower margins of ff. 105v-107v, to indicate the correct order of the text (bifolium 106-107 erroneously bound inside out, see Condition).

On the left pastedown is written the present shelfmark, 596 in brown ink; below Printed Cat. 1036, with the number of the manuscript in E. Bernard, Catalogi Manuscriptorum Angliae et Hiberniae, Oxoniae 1697; the number 1036 is written also on f. [I] recto.

On ff. [I] recto and II recto a table of contents of the manuscript is written in Greek, with references to the foliation; the same hand (John Caius?) wrote annotations in Greek and Latin on f. [VIII] verso: the last one mentions John Caius, suo dono Johanni Caii.

binding.p: Modern western binding. Full leather cover over millboard. Blind tooling on the boards (a triple line frame), and on the boards' edges. On the spine are pasted two paper labels with the two shelfmarks 455 (in red) and 596. 230 152 30
binding.condition: There are scrape marks on the covers.

origin.p:
The manuscript was copied by two contemporary hands probably
in the second half of the 15th century, as indicated by the watermarks and the scripts.

provenance.p: The manuscript was owned by John Caius (1510-1573) Caius, John, 1510-1573 (see Grierson 1978, p. 521).

history.acquisition: The manuscript was donated to the College Library by John Caius Caius, John, 1510-1573. On the left pastedown and on f. [I] recto (with handwritten shelfmark in red ink, 455) is pasted the Gonville and Caius College bookplate.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws partly on M. R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, vol. 2, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1908, pp. 628-629.
